h following a runaway accident two years earlier from which he had never fully recovered."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Returned from California Gold Rush after four years","body":"In 1849 — at age twenty-two — he left Illinois for the California Gold Rush. He returned to Illinois in 1853 to enter Knox College at Galesburg; the gold years did not make him wealthy but they made him a man who had crossed the continent twice before settling into farming."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Born in NY during family's CT-to-IL migration","body":"He was born August 1826 in Schenectady County NY — a temporary stop on the family's migration from Connecticut to Illinois. His parents were on the move; he and his eight older siblings together trace the path of a Connecticut Yankee family relocating westward in the second quarter of the nineteenth century."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Three of nine children died in infancy","body":"He and his wife Rebecca Fulton had nine children between 1858 and 1876. Three — George 1862, Richard 1869, and Josephine 1869 — died in infancy or as twin to a sibling who survived. The fifty-percent surviving rate of his infants reflected the brutal mortality of mid-century Illinois prairie childhood."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave Memorial 22076145","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/22076145/edward-mansfield"},{"label":"The Brimfield News, January 7, 1904 (obituary)"},{"label":"Mansfield scrapbook, Princeville Heritage Museum, #163.2019.123"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"edward-mansfield-sr-1826"},"HD3920":{"id":"HD3920","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Richard","last_name":"Mansfield","suffix":"Jr.","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Richard Mansfield Jr."},"birth":{"year":1790,"month":2,"day":1,"state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1868,"month":12,"day"